# ============================================================================
# Next major version — schema cleanup
# ============================================================================
# Drop transactions.user_id and scheduled_transactions.user_id. They are
# redundant with accounts.user_id (the account owner) and were retained in
# v1.15.0 only to keep many indexes/queries (idx_transactions_user_date,
# idx_transactions_user_sync, sync filters) working without a larger refactor.
# Real attribution lives in created_by_user_id.
#
# To do this safely:
#   1. Migrate every WHERE t.user_id = ? query to filter by account_id IN (...)
#      (most call sites already do this since v1.15.0 — audit the rest).
#   2. Update the Android sync layer to stop relying on user_id as a partition
#      key.
#   3. Drop the indexes that reference user_id, then drop the column.

# ============================================================================
# Scheduled-tx idempotency — done (v1.18.0) at the practical level
# ============================================================================
# v1.18.0 makes the scheduler write a deterministic client_id of the form
# "sched-<scheduled_id>-<next_occurrence>" on every materialization. The
# existing UNIQUE partial index on (created_by_user_id, client_id) rejects
# any re-fire as a UNIQUE constraint violation; the wrapping transaction
# rolls back, no balance double-count, no next_occurrence re-advance.
#
# A schema-level scheduled_transaction_id FK + UNIQUE(FK, date) partial
# index would be strictly stronger (lets the scheduled-tx UI derive
# "X/Y occurrences" from COUNT() instead of the brittle counter field).
# File as a fresh ticket if/when wanted.

